post_text: Do you want to develop a book reading habit?then these tips will be for you üëá.Growing everyday not physically but mentally also  üêí .....üßç.... üßòTip 1 - Try to find the type of books/genres that interest you. It could be fiction or nonfiction.Tip 2 - Once you find what to read define where and when to read Ex - I like to read after dinner everyday in the study room for 15-30 minutes.Tip 3 - Try to maintain a tracker where you can cross or mark your everyday progress. It will gives you the sense of accomplishment and satisfaction.Tip 4 - Do not try to complete the book if it does not excite you even after 50 pages, Because it's not only your responsibility to finish the book, the book itself has to be interesting so that we can complete it. Bonus Tip - Make it easy and obvious do not try to finish a book a day just start small 5-10 pages a day and if someday you haven't get time to read then don't feel guilty it's okay to miss somedays.#habitbuilding #readerscommunity #bookreader #learningeveryday #growingeveryday

post_text: Hello everybody and let me explain how did I improve my SSI from 32 to 61 in two weeks.1. My profile. I filled all the information that I could (it is important to have two profiles English and Russian, but both of it you have to fill in ENGLISH): - headline: short description of the position I'm looking for;- contact info: phone number, email, birthday and link to your LinkedIn profile - MUST;- filled all possible (5-five) position that I can apply - for those who are currently open to work;- filled the "About" form, wrote briefly and constructively, put all great outcomes such as cost savings, improving processes, speeding up Time to market, etc.;- explained all my expirience regarding IT: Company, position, breif description of the company, responsibility&key achievemnts;- filled an "Education" form (if you were graduated as a specialist, put in a form grade "Master's degree);- I mentioned skills that I possess and use with high efficiency - you must fill at least 20 skills;- asked for recommendations and gave a couple of it from myself;- filled a section with my language skills.2. Connections. Every day I add peers from the network of my current connections and using Additional searching engine of LinkedIn. Use the form "Search" on the top of your LinkedIn page, the fill the position (for example, Project manager) and after it choose the country and locations. You have to add people only WITH short cover message, not without any kind of words!3. Liked posts and commented it. I always update my home page and have a look on the posts of my Network. It is ipmortant to pay attention to like and write comments below these posts because it affects your SSI score. Use hashtags (especially #linkedin) in each message.4. Created my own posts. It is simple and last, but not the least. Whether I have any sort of a curious article or I want to share my current SSI, I make a post on my page and show/share it with my network. It is establishing of my brand here. I do all these things daily and it became as a routine. Will see how will it help me (or not).¬†The next step is to pump "Build relationships" block to 25 from 25.Feel free to ask any questions! #linkedin #profilebuilding #selfsufficiency #networking #connections #connectingpeople #brand #education #educationalleadership #ssi

post_text: Hello everyone on LinkedIn! Today I'd like to share my experience with a project I've been working on as a Junior+ Python web developer.The project is a web application that helps people manage their expenses. It allows users to add their income, expenses, and view statistics on their spending. It was developed using the Flask framework and PostgreSQL for the database.One of the challenges I faced during this project was designing the database schema. I had to ensure that the tables and relationships between them were set up in a way that would allow for efficient querying and easy maintenance. Additionally, I had to implement authentication and authorization to ensure that users could only access their own data.Another challenge was developing the user interface. I wanted to make it as user-friendly as possible, while also ensuring that it looked clean and professional. I used HTML, CSS, and Bootstrap for the front-end development, and JavaScript for some additional functionality.Despite the challenges, I am proud of what I was able to accomplish. It was rewarding to see the project come together and be used by real people. I also learned a lot about project management and working with a team, as I collaborated with other developers and a project manager to complete the project.Overall, this project was a great experience and it reinforced my passion for Python and web development. I'm excited to continue working on projects like this and to learn more along the way.Thanks for reading and I'd love to hear about your experiences with web development or any interesting projects you're working on. Let's connect and grow together! #team #webdevelopment #python #development #webdeveloper #project #opentowork #hunting #work #share #like #linkedin #projectmanagement #people #projects #maintenance #database #experience #statistics #html #css #javascript #data #love # # # #

post_text: Hello everyone on LinkedIn! My name is Hakob and I am excited to introduce myself as a Junior+ Python web developer.I'm sure you're already aware of how popular Python is in the programming world. And while I won't go into all the benefits of the language, I'd like to share my experience working with it.For me, Python is not just a programming language, but a way of thinking. In my opinion, it allows for complex tasks to be tackled more efficiently and simply than many other languages.Of course, as a Junior+ developer, I'm far from calling myself an expert in Python. post_text: #ChatGPT #FrontendDevelopment #frontend #React #ArtificialIntelligenceWe all know what a great tool ChatGPT is. As a React developer, I would like to share some practical usages I use myself for the tool below:1. Error debugging: Instead of waiting for a response to your Stack Overflow question or sifting through lengthy documentation, you can use ChatGPT to get instant help with debugging code. Simply provide the relevant code snippet to ChatGPT and ask your question, and the AI tool will provide you with a possible solution. If the response doesn't satisfy your query, ChatGPT can search the internet for an answer and provide you with an updated solution. No more time-consuming debugging!2. Array operations and function creation: ChatGPT can also be used as a low-code tool, allowing developers to describe a function's purpose and have ChatGPT provide the necessary code. For instance, when dealing with data retrieval from an API, ChatGPT can provide the necessary code to display object data in a card format, without the need for you to spend hours on boilerplate code.3. SEO text generation: ChatGPT can even generate SEO-friendly text that adheres to best practices. As developers, we know that crafting effective SEO copy is important but time-consuming. With ChatGPT, you can simply enter the necessary requirements and the AI tool will generate the text for you.That's all I have for today. Go try the tool already :D

post_text: Hit a stone wall and don't know how to get to the next level?Sometimes it's enough to strengthen your team to get more and better work done.We'll help you overcome the barrier, giving you a shoulder to lean on and take on some of the work related to the project management and development.In our work, we use an approach that allows different teams (Dev Team, Devops Team, QA Team, Management) to work independently of each other, while exchanging the information necessary for effective collaboration.The workflow is the same for each team, whereby:¬†¬†¬†‚Ä¢ The task setting process is standardized.¬†¬†¬†‚Ä¢ Roles and responsibilities are defined for all participants.¬†¬†¬†‚Ä¢ The process of interaction between the teams is clearly defined.¬†¬†¬†‚Ä¢ The same tool is used for creating and keeping track of all tasks, but each team has its own space and workflow.¬†¬†¬†‚Ä¢ The task statuses are also unified and clear.¬†¬†¬†‚Ä¢ All this allows us not to lose time when transferring work from one team to another and to use resources effectively, as a result of the work process transparency.Our managers see the whole picture, so they can plan the project more accurately and successfully release the final high quality products.To get more info about our superpowers, send us a message!

name: –ê–Ω–Ω–∞ –•–∞–Ω
title: Data scientist | Analyst | ML-engineer
post_text: The wave of popularity of chatGPT has reached me. The impression is shocking in the best sense of the word.Getting access to it cost me 45 rubles (instructions for bypassing the sanctions ban on Russian numbers can be easily googled).What I have tried:1. Foreign language lessonsThe chat suggested different options for practicing English, talked to me sincerely about books, asking pertinent questions. I also taught a couple of words in Japanese. I asked him to ask five words in English so that I would answer him in Japanese (romaji, to be exact). At first, the chat forgot to remove the translation for the suggested words, but after a couple of instructions I understood the exercise (and even apologized).2. Help in creating a chapter for Naruto fanfiction.According to the plot, I had to describe the celebration of the birthday of the heiress of the Hyuga clan and reveal on it the internal conflicts of its two branches. The chat helped with the plan of the holiday, and with the nature of the possible claims between the ninja. At the same time, taking into account the cultural characteristics of Japan and the world of Naruto.3. Junior Data Scientist CVVideos on YouTube lie - chat knows how to write a resume.My observations:1. Chat holds the context of the dialogue. It is not clear if he can lose it at all.2. Typical chat response: warning that the answer belongs to the machine -> multiple answers -> conclusion.3. There is an emotional color in speech, but of a weakly expressed positive character. Chat often emphasizes its technological nature. According to personal feelings, the ideal interlocutor for all those topics that do not interest your friends. Finally someone to talk to about this!4. Responds quickly in English. In response to Russian speech, he often answers in English. With a direct request to translate something into Russian (I assume this also applies to other languages), the response speed is significantly reduced.P.S. For fans of Naruto anime. I tried to get the chat to figure out how many people can be in the main and side branches and how the branch system works in the perspective of past generations (conditionally, how the main branch has not degenerated if everyone except the eldest child of the main family is stigmatized). Here the chat broke and could not solve the problem. I had to invent it myself :) With a competent series of questions, I'm sure the chat can help many writers with their incomprehensible dilemmas.#chatGPT #datascience #anime #ml

name: Vladimir Makhaev
title: Senior Software Developer
intro:
Have good experience in back-end mostly Golang and NodeJS, but can write number of other languages, like Lua, C#, C, Python, Rust looks promising, at some point it does not matter, you know. Databases mostly Mongo, Redis, Rabbit, but have played with number of others, like Postgres, Tarantool, Elastic Search, Clickhouse, Hadoop/Spark, Nats, Mysql, Sql Server, etc. Have experience of Devops Teamlead with estabilishing CI/CD for microservices and deep dive into Kubernetes. Worked with all major cloud providers: GCP, AWS, Azure and DIgital Ocean. Also have good experience with front-end (React and number of other frameworks) and React Native for mobile development. Creator of Amelisa (https://github.com/amelisa/amelisa) CRDT data engine. One of organizers of Moscow NodeJS Meetup (http://moscownodejs.ru/) and co-organizer of Moscow Kubernetes Meetup.Played different roles in different projects: developer, devops, front-end/designer, team lead, architect, project manager.Could be extremely helpful if you want to move to microservices and Kubernetes or already using them.Github: https://github.com/vmakhaevStack Overflow: https://stackoverflow.com/users/1336667/vladimir-makhaevHave good experience in back-end mostly Golang and NodeJS, but can write number of other languages, like Lua, C#, C, Python, Rust looks promising, at some point it does not matter, you know. Worked with all major cloud providers: GCP, AWS, Azure and DIgital Ocean. Also have good experience with front-end (React and number of other frameworks) and React Native for mobile development. Creator of Amelisa (https://github.com/amelisa/amelisa) CRDT data engine. One of organizers of Moscow NodeJS Meetup (http://moscownodejs.ru/) and co-organizer of Moscow Kubernetes Meetup.

Since May 2020 - team leader of the portal development team.

As a developer, I mainly deal with the backend - databases, architecture, etc.

In partnership with the Dutch Green Business <www.dgb.earth>, Green Zone International (GZI) Cameroon is currently implementing two projects: The Cameroon Afforestation Project 1 and the Sawa Cookstove Project. 

As Project Manager, I coordinate the following:  

The planting of 3 to 30 million trees (mostly fruit and nut trees) in various regions of Cameroon -- a carbon offset project that will run for 30 to 90 years. 

The manufacturing and distribution of 150,000 energy-efficient cookstoves in various regions of Cameroon. The cookstoves will reduce the use of charcoal by 60% and will be distributed for at least 3 years (2022 and 2024).

Support to farmers to plant and maintain trees as part of the Cameroon Afforestation Project.

The creation of transformation processes for the fruits and nuts from the farms -- increasing the incomes generated by farmers from their harvest. 

A "Community Solidarity Association (COMSA) Fund" in which part of the profits of Green Zone International Cameroon will be used for community development in areas where GZI activities are implemented. 

The engagement of communities all over Cameroon to participate in the Afforestation and Sawa Cookstove projects.

I have 12 years of experience in frontend development. Last 4 years I worked at the Frontend Team Lead position (React, Next, Vue).

My achievements:
- Created an very effective Frontend and QA team.

- Insisted on using Docker, which then saved a lot of time for all developers, QA and DevOps.

post_text: There are different types of servers that play important roles in managing and distributing data across networks. üî• Here are some basic server types and what they do: üí° üåê Origin Server: This server holds the original copy of a website or web application. When you access a website, your browser sends a request to the origin server, which then sends back the necessary files to display the site on your screen.üåê Proxy Server: A proxy server acts as an intermediary between a client and another server. It can help improve network performance by caching frequently accessed files and web pages, as well as filtering requests for security purposes.üìß Mail Server: This type of server manages the sending and receiving of email messages. When you send an email, your email client communicates with the mail server to deliver the message to the recipient's mail server.üåê Web Server: A web server is a software program that delivers web content, such as HTML pages and images, to web browsers. It listens for incoming requests from clients and sends back the appropriate responses.üîç DNS Server: A DNS server translates human-readable domain names (like "google.com") into IP addresses that computers can understand. When you type a URL into your browser, your computer sends a request to a DNS server to find the corresponding IP address.‚úÖ Understanding these basic server types can help you better navigate and troubleshoot network issues. post_text: It seems that the peak of the hype about the current version of chatGPT is over. And before OpenAI rolls out the next release, which in addition to text, seems to be able to do pictures and video, I want to voice a thought about the expectations of large language models. Someone finds a lot of the most unexpected applications for them, and someone says "chatGPT is a useless dumbass, doesn't know basic things, can't solve logical problems". But if you take what chatGPT can do as the part of the human brain that is responsible for speech, then chatGPT is already doing just fine. You don't have to expect outstanding abilities in logic, factual knowledge, mathematics, spatial orientation, etc.  As I see it, in solving the problem of creating general artificial intelligence, some chatGPT analogue will act as a convenient speech interface between humans, and more specialized things - "skills", like a notional Matlab, a data warehouse or home robot. Its task is to maintain the dialogue, translating from human to internal language of the respective skill, and vice versa.

post_text: Imagine if you could tell a ML model "play a funk bassline with a jazzy saxophone" and it would synthesize artificial music! Well actually, you don't need to imagine, you can just use it! Introducing RIFFUSION, a Stable Diffusion model trained on Spectrogram image data: https://lnkd.in/ge9_VE6t. The idea is simplistic: - just pick a pre-trained Stable Diffusion model (https://lnkd.in/dpFheWYS)- Take lot of musics with their text descriptions and convert that into Spectrogram image data- Fine-tune to the Stable Diffusion model=> you now have a model that can predict new spectrograms based on other spectrograms or text prompts. Just convert those spectrograms back to musics.¬† If you want more details on how to do it yourself you can follow the process here: https://lnkd.in/gpj_K-UF. I discovered this website yesterday through Alpha Signal's weekly summary: https://alphasignal.ai/. If you to learn more about stable diffusion, you can read my LinkedIn post on it: https://lnkd.in/gxBiU9fB---Follow me on Twitter: https://lnkd.in/eQ454QHD#machinelearning #datascience #stablediffusion

name: –ö—Å–µ–Ω–∏—è –ê–≥–µ–µ–≤–∞
title: –í–µ–¥—É—â–∏–π BI –ê–Ω–∞–ª–∏—Ç–∏–∫ - Tableau Certified Data Analyst
post_text: Last summer Tableau has announced a new Certified Tableau Data Analyst exam instead of a well-known Desktop Associate. And this is a story when I couldn't resist, and I needed to know what's insideIn a nutshell:- Three isolated sections, you should complete them one by one - can't double-check the responses once you complete the section- No more Internet, official knowledge base is available in the lab part only (as .pdf - but it is actually not needed there)- Rather easy hands-on lab - e.g. how to create a histogram, how to create a conditional set with TOP N- Tableau Desktop is not available in the first and third knowledge-based sections, so you can't practically check your suggestion - you need to recall syntax and the sequence of stepsWhat to pay attention to when preparing:- Calculations (types, syntax, applicability, you may be asked to select between TOTAL() and WINDOW_SUM())- Formatting - what actions should be sequentially applied to get the screen you see- Practice - check the Exam guide and practice everything that sounds unfamiliar to you More details are here (in Russian):https://lnkd.in/eS-5Cyx9and here:https://t.me/datanature#tableau #tableaucertified #data #businessintellegence

post_text: Why Exmo is a scam?Long story short: they're stealing your deposits to cover their losses.Long story. Kickico project was hacked on July 27, to be precise owning key of KICK coin smart contract was stolen and some tokens were burnt. Kickico project recovered access and promises to restore stolen/burnt tokens. Interesting token contract and very lucky guys. Really interesting thing starts next. Exmo.me crypto exchange also suffered a loss of KICK coins. And they started to lay their hands on KICK deposits which were sent *after* the hack, i.e. on coins which were perfectly safe. The scheme is the following: you send deposit, it is confirmed in Ethereum network, but you won't see it in your exmo wallet. Support is making excuses about technical maintenance (10 days of maintenance? C'mon), but I know that tokens were safe before transacting to exmo and don't need any maintenance. The likely root of the issue is that they're trying to cover (maybe temporal) expenses at the expense of users.The bottom line is that if you're using exmo‚Ää-‚Ääconsider more trusted exchange, otherwise you're exposing yourself to a high risk of theft or funds blocking.#blockchain¬†#scam¬†#exmo

intro:
I am person passionate about gaining new knowledge. I love to learn. As a programmer, I am passionate about bleeding-edge technologies.I am trying to experiment with every single technology I have a chance to work. Coding in Scala for Android with working ProGuard obfuscation? Sure! Compiling a working OS X Application with a Go binary with Cocoa bindings? Let‚Äôs make it possible. Exciting research tasks are the best tasks for me. Later, I have plans to reimplement it as a Progressive Web App too. post_text: Use React? Render large lists efficiently with react-window: https://lnkd.in/etNN94TH ~ a small library for virtualizing lists & grids. Renders what users can see vs. all your items at once.If you've used React Virtualized for this before, it's by the same author Brian Vaughn, (but is far smaller) and a better fit if targeting mobile web given the smaller library size. A quick Movies demo using react-window can be found here: https://lnkd.in/edAK3HR8I've enjoyed using react-window on a few projects where list virtualization was a better fit for the UX. There are of course trade-offs with infinite scrolling patterns like this (e.g. with CLS, Load More) and I've written about them here: https://lnkd.in/eQc8mGQyIn case you're interested in learning more about list virtualization in React with plenty of examples, there's a great guide over on web(dot)dev too by Houssein Djirdeh and Jason Miller: https://lnkd.in/erqqabkV :)#softwareengineering #javascript #webdevelopment

name: Rinat (4rontender) Valiullov
title: Frontend Developer
post_text: Payment through scanning QR code is very common but do you know how many ways there are to do it? There are 4 ways, no matter whether you‚Äôre using PayPal, Stripe, Paytm, WeChat, or Alipay. Is this surprising to you? To understand this, we will answer to questions. The first question is who presents the QR code:1. You can present the QR code and the merchant scans the code for payment. This is called ‚Äòconsumer-presented mode, and what the merchant does is direct debit your account.2. Obviously, the other way is that the merchant presents the QR code for you to scan to pay the due amount. This is called ‚Äòmerchant-presented mode‚Äô and you grant the direct credit from your account.The second question is whether the QR code is dynamic or static:1. A dynamic QR code means the QR code will be generated when you present it, or it will automatically regenerate every few seconds. Because it is dynamically generated, it may contain rich information, such as the amount due, transaction type, etc.2. A static QR code is generated once and used everywhere. Usually, it only contains the account information. So there are 2*2=4 ways to scan a QR code, which are:1. Consumer-presented mode + static QR code2. Consumer-presented mode + dynamic QR code3. Merchant-presented mode + static QR code4. Merchant-presented mode + dynamic QR codeI‚Äôve created an image to illustrate these 4 cases and their classic scenarios. üëâ Over to you: I‚Äôve marked one of the scan-to-pay scenarios with a red alert symbol to indicate that a risk is present. Do you know why it is high risk?¬†‚ÄîJoin a growing community of more than 100,000 readers who love System Design. Subscribe here: https://bit.ly/3FEGliw¬†#systemdesign #coding #interviewtips.

title: Frontend Developer
post_text: Soon you'll be able to use the secret behind Angular and NestJS Frameworks in vanilla JavaScript ü§Øüî•JS Decorators are finally moving forward in the language, it's been 4 years since the first idea, and in April it was promoted to TC39's Stage 3 ü§ØI built a super video tutorial showing in practice a very useful application that monitors all incoming HTTP requests and responses and plots the data on a graph from a terminal üò¨This is a complex functionality that will open your mind to think of much more use cases than just Logging User's actions with Decorators (as I see often when teaching about it)I say decorators are the secret for NestJS and Angular frameworks because they use them for almost everything.They inject dependencies, they build routes, they handle state, they override regular classes to become DB Entities, and much more.I think the Node.js project will also benefit as we can reuse a lot of code and intercept the default behavior of functions, classes, and properties with slight changes.In this video, I also will show you a library that helps a lot to build interfaces on the terminal, the blessed-contrib library.Ah and the last thing, I've been publishing blooper reels after the video so you can enjoy my recording mistakes in all my recent videos.Although today, even my cat came to distract me and to be part of the class üòπI hope you enjoy it!üëâüèª https://lnkd.in/dKMguVKCComment here, what are your opinions about JS Decorators, I'd love to discuss it with you about it!#javascript #tc39 #decorators #newstoday #video #tutorial #100daysofcode

post_text: [Reportedly] Elon Musk sent an email to the staff at Tesla with his 6 rules for productivity. Unsurprisingly, it leaked.Here they are:1) Avoid large meetingsLarge meetings waste valuable time and energy.- They discourage debate- People are more guarded than open- There‚Äôs not enough time for everyone to contributeDon‚Äôt schedule large meetings unless you‚Äôre certain they provide value to everyone.2) Leave a meeting if you‚Äôre not contributingIf a meeting doesn‚Äôt require your:- Input- Value- DecisionsYour presence is useless.It‚Äôs not rude to leave a meeting.But it‚Äôs rude to waste people‚Äôs time.3) Forget the chain of commandCommunicate with colleagues directly.Not through supervisors or managers.Fast communicators make fast decisions.Fast decisions = competitive advantage.4) Be clear, not cleverAvoid nonsense words and technical jargon.It slows down communication.Choose words that are:- Concise- To the point- Easy to understandDon‚Äôt sound smart. Be efficient.5) Ditch frequent meetingsThere‚Äôs no better way to waste everyone‚Äôs time.Use meetings to:- Collaborate- Attack issues head-on- Solve urgent problemsBut once you resolve the issue, frequent meetings are no longer necessary.You can resolve most issues without a meeting.Instead of meetings:- Send a text- Send an email- Communicate on a discord or slack channelDon‚Äôt interrupt your team‚Äôs workflow if it‚Äôs unnecessary.6) Use common senseIf a company rule doesn‚Äôt:- Make sense- Contribute to progress- Apply to your specific situationAvoid following the rule with your eyes closed.Don‚Äôt follow rules. Follow principles.üëâIf you like this post, please SHARE it, not COPY. Thanks #team #people #share #energy #like #communication #productivity #email #order #elonmusk #wisdom #quotes #quoteoftheday #managementconsulting #management #organisation #meeting #work #philosophy #principles

We are just lunching and as we saw - a lot of people in difficult financial situations now - so we made this service completely FREE. post_text: Real time bidding. New loss function.Online advertising , Real time bidding.In general there are two task in real time bidding.First is a task of optimizing requests choice, second is a optimizing bid prices.A first task answers on a question , what need to buy, to get a revenue.The revenue is get from the target events: Clicks, Conversions ‚Ä¶So we may make a model that predict the events. It‚Äôs a classification task and may be solve as usual classification problem of binary classification.A second task answers on a question , what price need, to get a more benefit and win an auction .I consider the second task.The second is more complex, need increase number of win bids. Because only a wining bid gives revenue.The trivial solution is to set a bid price little smaller then an expected benefit, for example smaller by 10 % . But this solution is not optimal when there is a limit of our budget, and limits our benefit with 10%.Not bad solution is predict a probability of win and if the probability smaller then a given value increase a bid price. It‚Äôs a classification task too.But there is another way. Lets try to find an optimal price of the bid that layers between the loss price and win price, said for the same requests. And then if the win probability for this bid price smaller then some value, we increase the bid price.At first glance, this is a regression problem. But there is one problem. We only know the cost of losing when we lose the auction, but we don't know the next win price. In another case, we know the winning price when we won the auction, but we do not know the price of the next loss.And in general the bid price is a function of an input request. That is a set of categorical and numerical values.Such as : exchange id, app id, city, hour, day of week, language , and so on.Our model need to predict an optimal price for each request.My approach is to use a custom loss function that solves the problem. (I called loss YuLoss.)The loss function is based with MSE loss with little changes, or may base with any other regression loss.The main idea is :If the prediction price less or equivale then the loss price we penalty our model.If the prediction price more then the loss price we don‚Äôt penalty our model with MSE loss.If the prediction price less or equavile then the win price we don‚Äôt penalty our model.If the prediction price more then the win price we penalty our model with MSE loss.MSE (target, prediction) , if prediction <= target and result == no win else 0YuLoss =MSE (target, prediction), if prediction > target and result == win else 0The Model was made with using Catboost lib:Inputs: a list of vectors of categorical features.Targets : a list of prices and results - win/ no win.Data set of 10 M rows.The solution has given the optimal prices that in sum less then initial prices on 70 %.By the way a win rate decrease only 5%.The experiment was made with A\ B test.

post_text: https://lnkd.in/g5Ft2UW5Random ml engineer thoughts on the regulation of the generative field in a thread, in short - at which level fair use ends? For me, description models like classification/segmentation/embedding ones seem fine.But the CLIP model is also descriptive, you can't reproduce images easily from this. SD used a pre-trained and freezed CLIP model, and CLIP itself seems as fair use.But even if you use just CLIP and optimize in pixel space you may reproduce Getty watermark or some artist style (vqvae+clip or disco diffusion or even old deep dream algo). And SD itself generates some styles not only because it used them during the training, but also because CLIP pretraining knows them already. So if CLIP is also not fair use we should start suing OpenAI.But CLIP is a "descriptive" model, so should we change the "fair use" of other descriptive models (like classification/segmentation/etc.), and how we can prove that smth was used and that model in pipeline influence someones "style" (CLIP or SD)?So no we can either ban all the "fair use" or not change it at all.

post_text: Doing a postdoc will not enhance your career prospects outside of academia. Just the opposite. It will damage your prospects. If you‚Äôre in a postdoc now, please don‚Äôt rationalize staying longer by telling yourself you have time to decide what to do next, or that your postdoc is somehow adding valuable experience. Top companies don‚Äôt want PhDs to gain even more academic experience. They want you to gain on the job training. And they want you to start now. I hate seeing PhDs chase low paying postdocs for years only to have it used against them when they finally realize they won‚Äôt ever be a tenured professor - or worse, they become tenured and quickly as ‚ÄúThis is it? I have to do the work of 10 people for half of what I would make in industry?‚Äù If you want to stay in a postdoc - that, of course, is up to you. But stay in it with eyes wide open knowing you are decreasing your viability in industry with each day that passes. #phd #phds #postdoc #postdocs #phdlife #phdchat #phdjobs #phdcareers #phdstudents #phdstudent #academicchatter
